<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06288144 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06288144 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  LOS-ANGELES; POLICE; VANDALISM; RULING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A police disciplinary board recommended one day of unpaid leave for an officerconvicted of vandalism in a much-publicized 1988 drug raid that left fourapartments in shambles.;   Prosecutors said Officer Charles Wilson, 38,originally concealed his role in the Aug. 1, 1988, raid in which policeofficers damaged walls, broke furniture, smashed windows and painted graffiti.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  L.A. COP PENALIZED IN VANDALISM CASEONE DAY UNPAID LEAVE ORDERED FOR OFFICER INDRUG-RAID DESTRUCTION  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     In an action commended by the police department's Board of Rights, he latercame forward and admitted his role in the raid.;   &quot;Your decision to be anisland of truth in a sea of dishonesty was a decision in support of moralityand integrity,&quot; said Cmdr. Martin Pomeroy, a member of the three-memberdisciplinary board. &quot;Telling the truth in these circumstances took courage andresulted in tremendous peer pressure, not to mention some jeopardy to yourproperty and upon you.;   &quot;Your car was vandalized and your paychecks weredestroyed. You were threatened by fellow officers face to face, and youreceived threatening phone calls at your home.&quot;;   In a finding releasedFriday, the board recommended that the six-year veteran be suspended for oneday after finding him guilty of improperly using a battering ram.;   Underdepartment regulations, Chief Daryl Gates can lessen but not increase therecommended penalty against Wilson, one of 80 officers involved in the raid at39th and Dalton streets.;   Wilson pleaded no contest in March to a singlecount of misdemeanor vandalism and was fined $2,500, ordered to perform 150hours of community service and sentenced to two years' probation.;   Wilson'splea came on the eve of a trial of three other officers who ultimately wereacquitted of vandalism.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Los Angeles  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911014  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  273  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, October 14, 199100288144,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>